## Re-Import System

**Re-import Asset (Update from Source):**
```
Right-click asset вҶ’ Re-import

System:
1. Checks if source file changed
2. Re-imports with same settings
3. Updates all instances automatically
4. Preserves material overrides
5. Shows what changed (diff)

Example:
"Character.glb has been updated
 - Added 2 new animations
 - Updated mesh geometry
 - Material count unchanged

 Re-import will update all instances.
 Continue?"

 [Yes] [No] [Review Changes]

The Point (Like Unreal Engine with Three.js)
Mesh Import System:

Drag & drop mesh files into Content Browser
Auto-detect format (GLTF, FBX, OBJ, etc.)
Import everything: mesh, skeleton, animations, materials, textures
Show 3D previews in Content Browser (thumbnails)
Preview animations in preview window
Drag to scene or add to actors
Re-import support (update from source file)

Asset Management:

Separate assets (mesh, skeleton, animations, materials)
Link relationships (animation вҶ’ skeleton вҶ’ mesh)
Reusable assets (one skeleton, many animations)
Organized folders (Meshes/, Animations/, Materials/, Textures/)

Animation Support:

Import animations from GLTF/FBX
Play animations via blueprint nodes
Blend animations smoothly
Preview animations in editor
Animation timeline control

Integration with Systems:

Works with Actor system (mesh components)
Works with Material system (PBR materials)
Works with Animation system (skeletal animation)
Works with Blueprint system (animation nodes)
Saves to JSON (asset metadata)
Works with project save/load

Integration Requirements:

Must use Three.js loaders (GLTFLoader, FBXLoader, OBJLoader)
Must work with Content Browser
Must show 3D preview thumbnails
Must extract and save all sub-assets (materials, textures, animations)
Must create proper asset hierarchy
Must support animation playback
Must work with project save/load system

Benefits:

Easy asset import (drag & drop)
Professional asset management
Full animation support
Three.js powered rendering
Reusable assets
Exactly like Unreal Engine workflow
